\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 The Foundational Reformulation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 What Conventional Finance Actually Assumes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Standard discounting rests on one axiom stated so casually it is rarely examined:\
$$V_t = V_T \\cdot e^\{-r(T-t)\}$$\
Unpacked, this says: a value received at a known, fixed future time T is worth less today by a factor that grows exponentially with the waiting time, at rate r. The rate r is treated as a property of time itself \'97 as if time has a price.\
But notice what this requires: 
\f1\b T must be known and fixed.
\f0\b0  The formula has no randomness in the delivery time. It discounts by how long you wait, not by how uncertain the waiting is. Interest is the price of known waiting.\
The Ackerer framework begins with a different assumption and never uses a fixed T at all:\
$$f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}
\f2\i t\\left[\\varphi(x
\f0\i0 \\theta)\\right]$$\
Here \uc0\u952  is random. There is no "waiting time" \'97 there is only a 
\f1\b probability distribution over when delivery occurs
\f0\b0 . The value today is not discounted by duration; it is the probability-weighted average of all possible delivery values across all possible delivery times.\
The philosophical shift is total. Under conventional finance, time costs money. Under the Ackerer structure, 
\f1\b time carries uncertainty, and uncertainty is fully described by the distribution of \uc0\u952 .
\f0\b0  No separate cost for waiting is needed or meaningful.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part I \'97 The Temporal Uncertainty Decomposition\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Theorem (Decomposition of Value)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Let \uc0\u952  have the exponential density under Q_a: $$q(\\theta = s \\mid \\mathcal\{F\}_t) = e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s , ds$$\
Then: $$f_t = \\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s \\cdot \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}_t[x_s] , ds$$\
Now define the 
\f1\b Temporal Uncertainty Operator
\f0\b0  $\\mathcal\{T\}
\f2\i \\kappa$ acting on any stochastic process $\{x_s\}
\f0\i0 \{s \\geq t\}$:\
$$\\mathcal\{T\}_\\kappa[x]_t := \\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s \\cdot \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}_t[x_s] , ds$$\
This operator has properties that are fundamentally different from conventional discounting. Let's derive them.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Property 1 \'97 Normalisation:
\f0\b0  $$\\mathcal\{T\}_\\kappa[\\mathbf\{1\}]_t = \\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s , ds = 1$$\
The operator integrates to 1 \'97 it is a genuine probability measure over time. Compare conventional discounting: $\\int_t^\\infty e^\{-r(s-t)\} \\cdot r , ds = 1$ only because r acts simultaneously as a discount rate AND a density normaliser. In the Ackerer framework these roles are separated: \uc0\u954  normalises the density, and there is no separate discount factor.\

\f1\b Property 2 \'97 Locality (no global time preference):
\f0\b0  $$\\frac\{\\partial\}\{\\partial \\kappa\} \\mathcal\{T\}_\\kappa[x]_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}
\f2\i t[x
\f0\i0 \\theta] \\cdot \\frac\{\\partial \\theta\}\{\\partial \\kappa\}$$\
As \uc0\u954  \u8594  \u8734 , the distribution of \u952  concentrates near t \'97 delivery is imminent and certain. As \u954  \u8594  0, the distribution spreads over all future time. 
\f1\b The "impatience" of the valuation is controlled entirely by \uc0\u954 , not by any interest rate.
\f0\b0 High \uc0\u954  = fast convergence = low temporal uncertainty. Low \u954  = slow convergence = high temporal uncertainty.\

\f1\b Property 3 \'97 Recursion (dynamic consistency):
\f0\b0  $$f_t = (1 - \\kappa_t , dt) \\cdot \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}
\f2\i t[f
\f0\i0 \{t+dt\}] + \\kappa_t , dt \\cdot x_t$$\
In continuous time: $df_t = \\kappa_t(x_t - f_t) , dt + dM_t$\
This says: the value today is a weighted mixture of (the expected value tomorrow if no delivery) and (the spot value if delivery occurs now). There is no interest accrual. Value evolves purely through the resolution of uncertainty about when delivery happens.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part II \'97 The Islamic Valuation Axioms\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 From this structure we can derive a complete axiomatic system for Islamic value theory \'97 one that is mathematically equivalent to no-arbitrage finance but philosophically grounded in Islamic principles.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Axiom 1 \'97 No Predetermined Excess (Anti-Riba)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 $$\\iota \\equiv 0$$ There exists no parameter in the valuation operator that creates value through the passage of time alone. Value changes only when the underlying asset changes or when the probability distribution of \uc0\u952  changes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Axiom 2 \'97 Transparency (Anti-Gharar)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The distribution of \uc0\u952  must be fully specified and observable: $$q(\\theta = s \\mid \\mathcal\{F\}_t) = e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s$$ No hidden parameters. The entire valuation model is determined by the observable \u954  process.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Axiom 3 \'97 Bilateral Risk (Anti-Maysir)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 For any contract, both parties must face genuine uncertainty: $$\\text\{Var\}^\{Q_a\}[\\varphi(x_\\theta)] > 0$$ A contract whose payoff has zero variance under Q_a is a pure rent \'97 indistinguishable from interest \'97 and is excluded.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Axiom 4 \'97 Grounding (Qabdh)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 There must exist a real asset $x_t$ such that the contract payoff is a function of it: $$\\varphi = \\varphi(x_\\theta), \\quad x_t \\in \\mathcal\{F\}_t^\{\\text\{real\}\}$$ Contracts are grounded in real asset values at the stopping time. Pure synthetics with no real asset reference are excluded.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Theorem (Uniqueness): Under Axioms 1\'964, the unique no-arbitrage price of any contract with payoff $\\varphi(x_\\theta)$ is $f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}
\f3\i t[\\varphi(x
\f1\i0 \\theta)]$.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is the Islamic pricing theorem. It says: given these four axioms \'97 which correspond precisely to the four Islamic prohibitions \'97 there is one and only one fair price, and it is the Ackerer formula.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part III \'97 The Islamic Yield Curve Without Interest\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Conventional yield curves plot interest rates r(T) against maturity T. The entire global fixed income market \'97 $130 trillion \'97 is built on this structure. Islamic finance has no equivalent because constructing a yield curve requires interest rates.\
The Ackerer framework enables an 
\f1\b Islamic Term Structure
\f0\b0  built on \uc0\u954  instead of r.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Construction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Define a family of perpetual sukuk indexed by convergence intensity \uc0\u954 : $$P(t, \\kappa) := f_t = \\frac\{\\kappa\}\{\\kappa + \\delta\} \\cdot x_t$$\
where \uc0\u948  = r_b - r_a is the rate differential (approximately zero for stablecoin-margined instruments).\
When \uc0\u948  \u8776  0, this simplifies to P(t, \u954 ) = x_t for all \u954  \'97 a flat term structure where every instrument equals spot. This is the Islamic ideal: 
\f1\b in a perfectly fair market, all instruments price at fair value regardless of tenor.
\f0\b0 \
In practice \uc0\u948  \u8800  0 and the term structure becomes: $$\\frac\{P(t, \\kappa)\}\{x_t\} = \\frac\{\\kappa\}\{\\kappa + \\delta\}$$\
This is a mapping from \uc0\u954  \u8712  (0, \u8734 ) to price/spot \u8712  (0, 1). As \u954  \u8594  \u8734 , price \u8594  spot. As \u954  \u8594  0, price \u8594  0.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 The Islamic yield curve is not a plot of interest rates against maturity. It is a plot of convergence intensity \uc0\u954  against the price-to-spot ratio.
\f0\b0  The "yield" is not a return for waiting \'97 it is an inverse measure of uncertainty about when delivery occurs.\
Inversion: given observed market prices P(t, \uc0\u954 ), we can back out the implied \u954  at every point: $$\\hat\{\\kappa\} = \\frac\{\\delta \\cdot P/x\}\{1 - P/x\}$$\
This gives the market's implied view of convergence intensity \'97 a term structure of temporal uncertainty. Central banks publishing this instead of interest rates would have a genuinely riba-free monetary policy signal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part IV \'97 Information Theory and the Entropy of Waiting\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Here is where the mathematics opens into something entirely new. The distribution of \uc0\u952 : $$q(s) = e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s$$\
is a probability density over time. It has an entropy: $$H(\\theta) = -\\int_t^\\infty q(s) \\ln q(s) , ds$$\
For constant \uc0\u954 , this evaluates to: $$H(\\theta) = 1 - \\ln(\\kappa)$$\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 The entropy of the waiting time is a decreasing function of \uc0\u954 .
\f0\b0  High \uc0\u954  = low entropy = low uncertainty about when delivery occurs. Low \u954  = high entropy = high uncertainty.\
This gives us a new interpretation of the price discount:\
$$\\frac\{f_t\}\{x_t\} = \\frac\{\\kappa\}\{\\kappa + \\delta\} = 1 - \\frac\{\\delta\}\{\\kappa + \\delta\}$$\
The discount from spot value is proportional to \uc0\u948 /\u954  \'97 the ratio of the rate differential to the convergence intensity. This is an 
\f1\b information ratio
\f0\b0 : how large is the rate uncertainty (\uc0\u948 ) relative to the temporal precision (\u954 )?\
When rate uncertainty dominates (\uc0\u948  >> \u954 ), the instrument trades well below spot. When temporal precision dominates (\u954  >> \u948 ), the instrument tracks spot closely.\
The entropy interpretation gives us a beautiful result: 
\f1\b the fair value of any Islamic financial instrument is determined by the ratio of its information uncertainty to its temporal precision.
\f0\b0  Richer information (higher \uc0\u954 ) means fairer pricing. This is the mathematics of Islamic transparency \'97 gharar as entropy, directly quantified.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part V \'97 Multi-Dimensional Stopping Times (Correlated Events)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The single stopping time framework handles one event. Most real financial problems involve multiple correlated events. Here the mathematics extends naturally.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 The Multi-Event Framework\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Let \uc0\u952 \u8321 , \u952 \u8322 , ..., \u952 \u8345  be a vector of stopping times with joint intensity matrix K: $$K_\{ij\} = \\text\{rate of event \} j \\text\{ occurring conditional on event \} i$$\
This is precisely the mathematics of 
\f1\b credit contagion
\f0\b0  \'97 how default of one entity affects the probability of default of others. In the conventional framework this requires interest rates. In the Ackerer extension it does not.\
Define the multi-event valuation operator: $$f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}
\f2\i t\\left[\\sum
\f0\i0 \{i=1\}^n \\varphi_i(x_\{\\theta_i\}) \\cdot \\mathbf\{1\}_\{\\theta_i < \\theta_j \\forall j \\neq i\}\\right]$$\
This is the expected payoff from whichever event arrives first, weighted by the probability that it arrives first.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Islamic application:
\f0\b0  A Musharakah with multiple partners, each with their own exit probability (\uc0\u952 \u7522 ), where one partner's exit affects the others. The entire Musharakah valuation \'97 with exit rights, preferential distributions, and correlated business risks \'97 is priced by this formula. No interest anywhere.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 The Correlation Structure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The joint density factors as: $$q(\\theta_1 = s_1, \\theta_2 = s_2) = q_1(s_1) \\cdot q_\{2|1\}(s_2 \\mid s_1)$$\
where the conditional density is: $$q_\{2|1\}(s_2 \\mid \\theta_1 = s_1) = e^\{-\\int_\{s_1\}^\{s_2\} (\\kappa_2 + \\lambda_\{12\}(s-s_1)) , du\} \\cdot (\\kappa_2 + \\lambda_\{12\}(s_2 - s_1))$$\
Here \uc0\u955 \u8321 \u8322  is the 
\f1\b contagion intensity
\f0\b0  \'97 how much \uc0\u952 \u8321  occurring accelerates \u952 \u8322 . This gives us the mathematics of:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Systemic risk in Islamic banking (one bank's problem accelerating others)\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Takaful claims clustering (one natural disaster triggering multiple claims)\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Supply chain sukuk (one supplier defaulting affecting the whole chain)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 All without interest. All with exact closed-form solutions derivable from the same Ito calculus used in the paper.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part VI \'97 The \uc0\u954 -SDF: A New Stochastic Discount Factor\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The most technically significant extension. In conventional asset pricing, the Stochastic Discount Factor (SDF) M_t prices everything: $$P_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^P_t[M_\{t+1\} \\cdot X_\{t+1\}]$$\
The SDF is typically derived as $M_\{t+1\} = e^\{-r\} \\cdot \\frac\{u'(c_\{t+1\})\}\{u'(c_t)\}$ \'97 the product of an interest discount and a marginal utility ratio. Interest is baked into the foundational pricing kernel of the entire economy.\
The Ackerer framework enables a 
\f1\b \uc0\u954 -SDF
\f0\b0  that contains no interest:\
$$\\mathcal\{M\}
\f2\i \{t,\\theta\} = \\frac\{d Q_a\}\{d P\}\\bigg|
\f0\i0 \{\\mathcal\{F\}
\f2\i \\theta\} \\cdot e^\{-\\int_t^\\theta \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa
\f0\i0 \\theta$$\
where the Radon-Nikodym derivative $dQ_a/dP$ captures risk preferences without requiring a risk-free rate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Properties of the \uc0\u954 -SDF:
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\mathbb\{E\}^P[\\mathcal\{M\}_\{t,\\theta\}] = 1$ \'97 properly normalised\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $P_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^P[\\mathcal\{M\}
\f2\i \{t,\\theta\} \\cdot X
\f0\i0 \\theta]$ \'97 prices any asset\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\mathcal\{M\}_\{t,\\theta\}$ depends only on \uc0\u954  and the Radon-Nikodym derivative \'97 
\f1\b no r appears anywhere
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This is the Islamic Stochastic Discount Factor. It is the fundamental object of a complete Islamic asset pricing theory \'97 analogous to the Arrow-Debreu state price density in conventional finance, but constructed without any interest rate.\
Every asset pricing result in conventional finance \'97 the CAPM, the APT, the pricing of all derivatives \'97 has an analogue in the \uc0\u954 -SDF framework. The research programme is vast. The mathematics is mature enough (it is just stochastic calculus on the filtered probability space) to develop fully.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part VII \'97 The Wasserstein Distance and Optimal Transport\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is the deepest mathematical extension, connecting the Ackerer framework to optimal transport theory.\
The Temporal Uncertainty Operator $\\mathcal\{T\}_\\kappa$ maps a distribution over asset values to a present value. Different values of \uc0\u954  give different present values. The space of all such valuations \'97 parameterized by \u954  \'97 forms a metric space.\
The natural metric on this space is the 
\f1\b Wasserstein distance
\f0\b0  between the distributions $q_\{\\kappa_1\}$ and $q_\{\\kappa_2\}$:\
$$W_2(q_\{\\kappa_1\}, q_\{\\kappa_2\}) = \\left(\\inf_\{\\gamma \\in \\Gamma\} \\int |s_1 - s_2|^2 , d\\gamma(s_1, s_2)\\right)^\{1/2\}$$\
This measures how different two valuations are, not in terms of price difference but in terms of the 
\f1\b distance between the underlying temporal uncertainty structures
\f0\b0 . Two instruments with the same price but different \uc0\u954  values are genuinely different in the Wasserstein sense \'97 they represent different distributions of waiting.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Islamic finance application:
\f0\b0  The Wasserstein distance gives a rigorous measure of gharar. Two instruments with the same expected payoff but different Wasserstein distances represent different levels of uncertainty. A fatwa could, in principle, specify a maximum acceptable Wasserstein distance \'97 a mathematical definition of tolerable gharar.\
The optimal transport problem between $q_\{\\kappa_1\}$ and $q_\{\\kappa_2\}$ finds the 
\f1\b minimum cost transformation
\f0\b0 from one temporal uncertainty distribution to another. This is the mathematics of 
\f1\b contract transformation
\f0\b0  \'97 how to restructure a financially identical but Shariah-noncompliant instrument into a compliant one at minimum cost. The Kantorovich duality gives the dual problem as a pricing problem \'97 exactly the no-arbitrage condition of the Ackerer framework appears as the dual constraint.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Part VIII \'97 The Grand Unified Equation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Pulling everything together, we can write a single equation that contains all of the above:\
$$\\boxed\{f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}^\{Q_a\}_t\\left[\\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u , du\} \\cdot \\kappa_s \\cdot \\varphi(x_s, \\mathbf\{Z\}_s, \\mathcal\{I\}_s) , ds\\right]\}$$\
Where:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\varphi$ is 
\f1\b any
\f0\b0  payoff function (futures, options, takaful, sukuk, pension, zakat...)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $x_s$ is the primary real asset (commodity, equity, RWA...)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\mathbf\{Z\}_s = (Z_s^1, ..., Z_s^n)$ is a vector of correlated secondary assets (for quanto, multi-asset, baskets...)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\mathcal\{I\}_s$ is an information process (for asymmetric information, insider knowledge...)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\kappa_s > 0$ is the convergence intensity (can itself be stochastic \'97 see Part VI)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 $\\iota \\equiv 0$ \'97 
\f1\b always and everywhere absent
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
